🔩 List of Components with Explanation of Their Functions:
1.	ESP32 Microcontroller Board
o	Acts as the central processing unit. It reads analog input from the potentiometer, interprets it as health data, drives the OLED display, and manages the LED and buzzer alerts. Also offers Wi-Fi capability for potential IoT upgrades.
2.	Potentiometer Placeholder //  MAX30100
o	Simulates sensor values. Rotating the knob changes resistance, which the ESP32 reads as analog voltage, representing either heart rate or SpO₂ readings.
3.	0.96" I2C OLED Display (SSD1306)
o	Displays the simulated heart rate and SpO₂ readings in real-time, providing a clear visual output of the system’s operation.
4.	Red LED
o	Lights up when the simulated health readings cross critical thresholds, serving as a visual warning indicator.
5.	Green LED
o	Lights up when the readings are within safe and healthy ranges.
6.	Buzzer (Active Type)
o	Sounds an audible alert whenever abnormal readings are detected, enhancing the warning system.
7.	Push Button
o	Allows manual user interaction. Pressing the button resets the alert system and can stop the buzzer.
8.	Breadboard and Jumper Wires
o	Used for prototyping. Allows easy, solderless connections between the ESP32 and other components.

